<p>On Tuesday we released the latest version of the
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/http://article-level-metrics.plos.org/">PLOS
Article-Level Metrics application</ext-link>. As always, the source code
is available at
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/https://github.com/articlemetrics">Github</ext-link>.
The changes in this version focus on improving API performance, making
it easier to install the application, and RSS feeds for the most popular
articles by source and publication date (e.g.
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/http://alm.plos.org/sources/twitter.rss?days=7">the
most tweeted papers published in the last 7 days</ext-link>). See the
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/https://github.com/articlemetrics/alm/wiki/2.6">Github
Wiki page</ext-link>for more details, in the Wiki you also find the
development
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/https://github.com/articlemetrics/alm/wiki/Roadmap">roadmap</ext-link>
and the
<ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170731155505/https://github.com/articlemetrics/alm/issues">issue
tracker</ext-link> for feature suggestions.</p>
